Project Description

Now that youve learned about basic data manipulation in R, its time to learn how to input a data file into R and learn the concept of data frame.

Learn how to read various data files, such as text, CSV, and Excel.

Refer to the Data Camp tutorial. You can always get help for a command by typing ?[command] (eg: ?read.csv) in the RStudio Console

# Solution from StackOverflow:
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1523126/how-to-read-data-when-some-numbers-contain-commas-as-thousand-separator

setClass("num.with.commas")
setAs("character", "num.with.commas", 
        function(from) as.numeric(gsub(",", "", from) ) )
df_text <- read.table("Facebook Friends.txt", skip = 1, header = TRUE, sep = '\t', 
                      skipNul = TRUE, colClasses=c('num.with.commas'))

# Note: I noticed a few columns were "factors".  It turned out that these had "thousands" numbers with commas in them.  I did some reasearch and changed the way that i did the import, fixing this on the import vs. here.
  1. Create a data frame from the CSV data frame, using subset that includes 3 fields: Gender, Posts, Friends. Include only valid Gender values (Male=1; Female=0). Use head to display the top records. (see: Quick-R: Data Management)
df1 <- subset(df_csv, Gender == 0 | Gender == 1, select=c('Gender','Posts', 'Friends'))
